                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d792">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/154</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Kirby Lumber Company</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Houston, Texas</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-05">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 5, 1914</hi>.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>Telegraph companies refuse to handle code messages for Porto Rico advising French
                    cable New York to Porto Rico regulations demand plain language and full address.
                    Must these revisions be complied with on messages from one part of United States
                    to another? We, of course, considering Porto Rico United States territory and
                    business in a sense interstate.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirby Lumber Company</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
